</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C354656399491128FD76FF72FB71FE93" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF136E899491128FD76FF72FB71FE93" blockId="72.[700,1229,193,333]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
ETYMOLOGY: The specific epithet is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D6B99491128FC9CFE97FC18FEEE" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[819,939,281,304]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangulus">
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA99491128FC9CFE97FC18FEEE" box="[819,939,281,304]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">triangulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(having three angles). I refer to the trigonal shape of the pygidium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
